            <bug_when>2008-06-05 08:59:08 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>The openMode property of the new tree needs usability improvements. Finally there are only two common behaviors: single or double clicking. It would be OK, to just allow these two through a (maybe boolean) property.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>3233</commentid>
            <who name="Fabian Jakobs">fabian.jakobs</who>
            <bug_when>2008-06-09 14:47:01 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>to me</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>3235</commentid>
            <who name="Fabian Jakobs">fabian.jakobs</who>
            <bug_when>2008-06-09 14:56:18 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>I don&#39;t really see a need for this change. There are currently five modes implemented, which are all functional and tested. Why should we cut working and sensible features?</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>3236</commentid>
            <who name="Sebastian Werner">info</who>
            <bug_when>2008-06-09 14:58:00 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>It&#39;s simply to much. Half of them make no sense and are that uncommon that nobody really needs them. Would be interesting what other toolkits do here. The current implementation seems relatively self-brewed.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>3238</commentid>
            <who name="Fabian Jakobs">fabian.jakobs</who>
            <bug_when>2008-06-09 17:37:34 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>OK, from the five modes we need at least these:

 - single click open close
 - double click open close
 - none (does not open/close on mouse clicks)
 
 I can remove the other ones but we cannot make this a boolean property</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>3239</commentid>
            <who name="Sebastian Werner">info</who>
            <bug_when>2008-06-09 17:44:00 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>Just wondering. What&#39;s the reason for &quot;none&quot;? Is this an option available anywhere else? What&#39;s the idea behind. Thanks.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>3241</commentid>
            <who name="Fabian Jakobs">fabian.jakobs</who>
            <bug_when>2008-06-09 18:01:37 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>e.g. Apple Mail: a double click make the tree item editable and a single click has no effect

most tree items in OS X don&#39;t open the folder on click or double click</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>3242</commentid>
            <who name="Sebastian Werner">info</who>
            <bug_when>2008-06-09 18:48:18 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>Ah cool. Never found this out before. Interesting. Mhh, lead me to the idea to have a named property following the &quot;emulation&quot; with values:

&quot;legacy&quot;, &quot;modern&quot; and &quot;mac&quot; 

legacy=double click
modern=single click
mac=no click

&quot;modern&quot; should be the default IMHO.

Sometimes both options work e.g. double click also closed under single click environments, so the value named according to the open behavior may not work that well.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
